@incollection{Thompson2013,
abstract = {Pools and riffles are important bedforms that are one of the most recognized features in rivers having less than 0.02 gradient. Pools are classified as deep areas with low velocities at low stage, whereas riffles exhibit higher water-surface slopes and faster velocities. Pools and riffles exist in both alluvial and bedrock channels, but are best developed in gravel-bed substrates and meandering channels. These undulations in bed topography provide the primary framework for aquatic habitat in channels, and are of great interest because of their importance for macro-invertebrates and fish species. An increasing number of articles propose that convergence of flow and enhanced turbulent conditions are necessary conditions for pool–riffle formation. Complex hydraulic patterns lead to a skewed distribution of feature-to-feature distances that tend to average five-to-seven bankfull widths apart. Pool depth, length, and volume tend to increase with larger drainage area and decrease with more sediment supply. Few details of controls on riffle geometry are presently known. The sequences eventually create stage-dependent form resistance with higher forces in pools at high flow and sediment-sorting patterns that maintain the morphology and enhance habitat complexity.},
